Unsupervised Learning on Global Cancer Patient Data (2015-2024)¶

This notebook performs an unsupervised learning analysis on the Global Cancer Patient Dataset (2015-2024), sourced from https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/zahidmughal2343/global-cancer-patients-2015-2024. The dataset comprises cancer patient records with numerical predictors (e.g., Age, Genetic_Risk, Air_Pollution, Alcohol_Use, Smoking, Obesity_Level, Treatment_Cost_USD, Survival_Years) and categorical variables (e.g., Gender, Country_Region, Cancer_Type, Cancer_Stage).

The analysis aims to:

  • Identify key risk factors using PCA and SVD.
  • Reconstruct missing data via matrix completion.
  • Detect anomalies in patient records.
  • Determine top predictors of patient outcomes.
  • Visualize correlations among features.
  • Group patients into risk profiles using clustering.

Techniques applied include PCA, SVD, Isolation Forest, hierarchical clustering, and K-Means clustering.

3. Data Preprocessing¶

Prepare and clean the data logically:

  • Separate numerical and categorical features.
  • Impute missing values (median for numerical, most frequent for categorical).
  • Standardize numerical features.
  • Encode categorical variables for clustering.
In [5]:
# Define numerical and categorical columns
numerical_cols = ['Age', 'Genetic_Risk', 'Air_Pollution', 'Alcohol_Use', 
                  'Smoking', 'Obesity_Level', 'Treatment_Cost_USD', 'Survival_Years']
categorical_cols = ['Gender', 'Country_Region', 'Year', 'Cancer_Type', 'Cancer_Stage']

# Ordinal encoding for Cancer_Stage
stage_mapping = {'Stage 0': 0, 'Stage I': 1, 'Stage II': 2, 'Stage III': 3, 'Stage IV': 4}
data['Cancer_Stage'] = data['Cancer_Stage'].map(stage_mapping)

# Impute missing values
num_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='median')
data[numerical_cols] = num_imputer.fit_transform(data[numerical_cols])

cat_imputer = SimpleImputer(strategy='most_frequent')
data[categorical_cols] = cat_imputer.fit_transform(data[categorical_cols])

# Standardize numerical features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_num_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(data[numerical_cols])
X_num_scaled_df = pd.DataFrame(X_num_scaled, columns=numerical_cols, index=data.index)

# Encode categorical features for clustering
label_encoders = {}
for col in categorical_cols:
    le = LabelEncoder()
    data[col] = le.fit_transform(data[col])
    label_encoders[col] = le

# Combine standardized numerical and encoded categorical features
X_full = pd.concat([X_num_scaled_df, data[categorical_cols].reset_index(drop=True)], axis=1)

print("\nShape of Combined Feature Set for Clustering:", X_full.shape)

Shape of Combined Feature Set for Clustering: (50000, 13)

5. Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) for Matrix Completion¶

Simulate missing data and reconstruct it using SVD:

  • Tune rank k and evaluate with MSE.
In [9]:
# Simulate missing data (10% NaNs)
X_missing = X_num_scaled.copy()
mask = np.random.random(X_missing.shape) < 0.1
X_missing[mask] = np.nan

# SVD-based matrix completion function
def matrix_completion(X, k=3, max_iter=10):
    X_filled = SimpleImputer(strategy='mean').fit_transform(X)
    for _ in range(max_iter):
        U, S, Vt = svd(X_filled, full_matrices=False)
        S_k = np.diag(S[:k])
        X_reconstructed = U[:, :k] @ S_k @ Vt[:k, :]
        X_filled[mask] = X_reconstructed[mask]
    return X_filled

# Perform matrix completion with tuned k=3
X_imputed = matrix_completion(X_missing, k=3)

# Evaluate with Mean Squared Error (MSE)
mse = np.mean((X_num_scaled[mask] - X_imputed[mask]) ** 2)
print(f"\nMatrix Completion MSE: {mse:.4f}")

Matrix Completion MSE: 1.7151

9. Hierarchical Clustering¶

Perform hierarchical clustering:

  • Tune linkage methods and number of clusters with dendrograms.
  • Evaluate cluster characteristics.
In [17]:
# Use a smaller subset for dendrogram visualization (1000 samples max)
subset_size = min(1000, len(X_full))  # Adjust based on your dataset size
subset = X_full.sample(subset_size, random_state=42)

print(f"Creating dendrograms with {subset_size} samples...")

# Plot dendrograms for different linkage methods (optimized)
linkage_methods = ['ward', 'complete', 'average']
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(18, 5))

for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    print(f"Computing {method} linkage...")
    Z = linkage(subset, method=method, metric='euclidean')
    
    # Create dendrogram with more aggressive truncation
    dendrogram(Z, 
              ax=axes[i],
              truncate_mode='level', 
              p=2,  # I Reduced this from 3 to 2 levels in an attempte to reduce time
              show_leaf_counts=True,
              leaf_font_size=8)
    
    axes[i].set_title(f'Dendrogram - {method.capitalize()} Linkage')
    axes[i].set_xlabel('Samples')
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Distance')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# For full dataset clustering, I used AgglomerativeClustering (much faster than linkage matrix)
print(f"Fitting hierarchical clustering on full dataset ({len(X_full)} samples)...")

# Use connectivity to speed up computation.
from sklearn.neighbors import kneighbors_graph
if len(X_full) > 2000:  
    print("Using k-neighbors connectivity for faster computation...")
    connectivity = kneighbors_graph(X_full, n_neighbors=10, include_self=False)
    hierarchical = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, 
                                         linkage='ward', 
                                         connectivity=connectivity)
else:
    hierarchical = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=4, linkage='ward')

# Fit and predict
hier_clusters = hierarchical.fit_predict(X_full)
data['Hier_Cluster'] = hier_clusters

print("Hierarchical clustering completed!")

# Analyze cluster characteristics
hier_cluster_means = data.groupby('Hier_Cluster')[numerical_cols].mean()
print("\nHierarchical Cluster Means (Numerical Features):")
print(hier_cluster_means)

# Quick cluster size summary
cluster_sizes = pd.Series(hier_clusters).value_counts().sort_index()
print(f"\nCluster sizes:")
for i, size in cluster_sizes.items():
    print(f"Cluster {i}: {size} patients ({size/len(data)*100:.1f}%)")

# Compare with K-means for validation
print("\nRunning K-means for comparison...")
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=42, n_init=10)
kmeans_clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(X_full)

# Check similarity between hierarchical and k-means clustering
from sklearn.metrics import adjusted_rand_score
similarity = adjusted_rand_score(hier_clusters, kmeans_clusters)
print(f"Similarity between Hierarchical and K-means clustering: {similarity:.3f}")
print("(1.0 = identical, 0.0 = random)")

10. K-Means Clustering¶

Apply K-Means clustering:

  • Tune k using elbow method and silhouette score.
  • Evaluate and visualize clusters.
In [22]:
# Elbow method to tune number of clusters
inertia = []
k_range = range(1, 11)
for k in k_range:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=42)
    kmeans.fit(X_full)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)

# Plot elbow curve
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(k_range, inertia, marker='o')
plt.title('Elbow Plot for K-Means Clustering')
plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters (k)')
plt.ylabel('Inertia')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# Fit K-Means with optimal k (e.g., 4) and evaluate with silhouette score
optimal_k = 4
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=optimal_k, random_state=42)
clusters = kmeans.fit_predict(X_full)
data['Cluster'] = clusters

sil_score = silhouette_score(X_full, clusters)
print(f"\nSilhouette Score for K-Means (k={optimal_k}): {sil_score:.4f}")

# Visualize clusters in PCA space
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.scatter(X_pca[:, 0], X_pca[:, 1], c=clusters, cmap='viridis', alpha=0.5)
plt.title('K-Means Clusters in PCA Space')
plt.xlabel('PC1')
plt.ylabel('PC2')
plt.colorbar(label='Cluster')
plt.show()

# Evaluate cluster characteristics
cluster_means = data.groupby('Cluster')[numerical_cols].mean()
print("\nK-Means Cluster Means (Numerical Features):")
print(cluster_means)
